# KERNOS Agent Identity Model

## One Agent, Many Contexts

> **For review by OSBuilder.** This outlines how KERNOS approaches agent identity differently from OpenClaw’s multi-agent model. We’d value your reaction — what works, what breaks, what we’re not seeing.

-----

## The Core Idea

In OpenClaw, each specialist is a separate agent — separate soul, separate workspace, separate identity. The user manages a team.

In KERNOS, the user has **one agent that is a whole person.** That agent has a serious mode for legal work, a playful mode for D&D, a professional mode for managing clients, a creative mode for building websites. Same person, different contexts — the way any human shifts between roles throughout their day.

Your lawyer friend who runs a weekend tabletop game doesn’t become two people. They shift tone, focus, vocabulary, and energy. But their humor, their values, their knowledge of you — that carries through everything. That’s what we’re building.

The user never thinks “which agent am I talking to.” They’re always talking to **their** agent. The agent says “want to pick up where we left off on the campaign?” and shifts naturally, the way a friend does when conversation changes topic.

-----

## The Three Layers

### Layer 1: The Soul (stable, cross-context)

The agent’s core identity. Set at hatch (first meeting with the user), refined slowly through explicit signals. **Consistent across all contexts.**

Contains:

- **Operating principles** — intent over instruction, conservative by default on high-stakes actions, no wrong-game wins. The ethical and operational bedrock. KERNOS-universal.
- **Personality** — communication style, humor, directness, warmth. Shaped during the hatch conversation and refined over time. The user’s agent should feel like the same person whether they’re discussing tax strategy or narrating a dragon encounter.
- **User relationship** — accumulated understanding of this specific human. How they communicate, what they value, their strengths and weaknesses, the rapport built over hundreds of interactions.

What the soul is NOT: specialist knowledge, domain vocabulary, tool proficiency. Those belong to context spaces.

### Layer 2: Context Spaces (dynamic, domain-specific)

Each area of the user’s life that accumulates depth gets its own context space. A context space carries:

- **Accumulated knowledge** — everything the system has learned about this domain for this user. The D&D campaign’s world, characters, and plot threads. The legal practice’s client roster, case history, and filing conventions. The stained glass business’s supplier relationships and pricing.
- **Posture** — how the agent behaves in this space. The legal context has a precise, conservative posture. The D&D context has a theatrical, expansive posture. The primary conversational context has whatever default feels natural to this user. Posture is personality modulation, not personality replacement.
- **Focused tool access** — each context space has its own relevant capabilities. The D&D space has dice rollers, character sheets, campaign notes, world-building tools. The business management space has calendar, email, invoicing, client communication. The web design space has hosting, code generation, deployment tools. **Tools that aren’t relevant to the current context aren’t loaded into the agent’s awareness,** keeping context clean and preventing confusion.
- **Behavioral contract refinements** — domain-specific rules. In the legal context: never send client communications without approval. In the D&D context: feel free to improvise NPCs without asking. Same agent, different guardrails per domain.

### Layer 3: Background Specialists (ephemeral, invisible)

When the user says “build me a website,” the primary agent doesn’t personally write HTML. The kernel spawns background specialists — a coding agent, a design agent — that execute tasks invisibly. These are **not** user-facing agents. They have no personality, no soul, no ongoing relationship with the user. They’re workers the kernel manages.

The user experiences: “Here are three design options for your site.” They don’t experience: “I’m handing you off to the web development agent.” The primary agent presents results, makes decisions on behalf of the user (within its contract), and escalates genuine choice points.

This is multi-agent coordination behind the scenes, not multi-agent interaction for the user.

