## What This Looks Like Over Time

### Week 1

One context space: general conversation. Agent learns the user’s communication style, work patterns, basic needs. Calendar connected. Soul is forming but still generic.

### Month 1

Two or three context spaces emerging naturally. The business management space has accumulated client knowledge and scheduling patterns. Maybe a personal/family space is forming. Email connected. Soul is calibrated — the agent has a distinct personality that feels like “theirs.”

### Month 6

Five or six context spaces with real depth. The business space knows every client by name. The D&D campaign has 20 sessions of accumulated lore. The legal context has case history and filing patterns. A hobby space tracks stained glass projects and supplier relationships. The agent has evolved from assistant to something closer to a knowledgeable partner.

### The moat

A new service can replicate the tools. They can’t replicate six months of accumulated context across every domain of someone’s life. The soul — the specific personality calibrated to this specific person — is irreplaceable. That’s memory as the moat.

